class Solution {
    public int numDecodings(String s) {
        int[] dp = new int[s.length()];
        if (s.charAt(0) != '0'){
            dp[0] = 1;
        } else{
            return 0;
        }
        if (s.length() > 1 && s.charAt(1) != '0'){
            if ((s.charAt(0) - '0') * 10 + (s.charAt(1) - '0') <= 26){
                dp[1] = 2;
            } else{
                dp[1] = 1;
            }
        } else if (s.length() > 1 && s.charAt(1) == '0'){
            if ((s.charAt(0) - '0') * 10 + (s.charAt(1) - '0') <= 26){
                dp[1] = 1;
            } else{
                dp[1] = 0;
            }
        }
        for (int i = 2; i < s.length(); i++){
            if (s.charAt(i) != '0'){
                dp[i] = dp[i] + dp[i - 1];
            }
            if (s.charAt(i - 1) != '0' && (s.charAt(i - 1) - '0') * 10 + (s.charAt(i) - '0') <= 26){
                dp[i] = dp[i] + dp[i - 2];
            }
        }
        return dp[s.length() - 1];
    }
}

/*
Notes:

(Using “Dynamic Programming”)

Value functions of Q91: 
  F ( i )’ = F ( i – 1 )                     IF “ i != 0 ” 
  F ( i )’’ = F ( i – 2 )                    IF “ arr[i-1] * 10 + arr[i] <= 26”
  F( i ) = F( i )’ +F( i )’’
 
Explanation: 
  The dp value of current index represents the result of substring (From index 0 to current index).
    Case 1: If the character of current index is not “0”, means we it can be an independent alphabet and add to the last substring (index - 1). In this case, the dp value of current index equals to the value of “index-1”.
    Case 2: If the number composes of “current index” and the “index-1“is less than 26(between “A-Z”), which means “current index” and “current index - 1” can be a new alphabet and add to former substring (index - 2). In this case, the dp value of current index equals to the value of “index - 2”.
    To sum up, the dp value of current index equals to the sum of Case1 and Case2.

*” Boundary condition”: 
  1. Passing particular value into dp[0].
  2. Passing particular value into dp[1].
  3. Start from index 2 instead of 0.


*/
